            <personal-details:content>My name is Philip Bond and I am junior studying mechanical engineering at Tennessee Technological University with the intent of graduating in May of 2019.
	My main area of research interest is additive manufacturing. My first introduction to 3D-printing was actually samples printed at the Lab. This piqued my curiosity and I have been interested ever since. As I learned more about additive manufacturing and about the amazing things (such as the 3D-printed Shelby Cobra) that the Lab has been able to accomplish at the Manufacturing Demonstration Facility, I knew it was where I wanted to do my research. 
	Another area that I would be interested in researching would be materials science. In one of the classes that I took this past summer, namely Materials and Processes in Manufacturing, I learned about the fascinating field of materials science. The way that materials could have different properties based on unique microstructures and forming techniques intrigued me. When I found that the Oak Ridge National Lab did extensive research in that area, I realized that it could be a place where I would be able to expand on my interest.
	I hope to be employed by the Oak Ridge National Laboratory soon after I graduate with the intent of pursuing a career in either materials science or manufacturing technology at ORNL's Manufacturing Demonstration Facility. Aided by an outstanding education received at Tennessee Tech, I will become an indispensable part of the innovative team there. Eventually, I hope to achieve a position in management to lead others in making practical scientific advancements in industry that will push the United States to the forefront of innovative technology. By participating in the HERE program as an ORISE intern, I will gain important experience and familiarity at the Manufacturing Demonstration Facility that will allow me to begin contributing to the improvement of the Oak Ridge National Lab as soon as I am hired.</personal-details:content>
        </person:biography>
